Session close. You got there yourself — the line moved from *domain* (file vs. articulation) to *function* (revelation vs. confirmation), and that's the version worth banking. What you're tracking isn't timing and isn't question-shape; it's whether the next line still *does* what you scheduled it to do, given what the learner has already put on the table. Three notes, one keep among them, and a patch.

**Note 1 is the headline.** The check runs at the top of every scripted beat, reveal or elicitation alike: has the learner already spoken this thing? If yes, the beat's illocutionary act has silently converted, and you play it as confirmation — *"yes, that's exactly what the mortar shows"* — same file order, same withheld crowsfoot, different act. T9 and T12 both failed this, in different registers.

**Note 2 is your own tripwire**, kept because it's cheap to run mid-performance even if it only catches one subclass: when your question reproduces the shape of the previous one, suspect you're executing a pattern rather than reading the room. It won't catch T9 (a reveal repeats no shape) — that's why it's the tripwire, not the check.

**Note 3 is the keep.** T22 is the one place withholding paid a dramatic dividend instead of deferring one. Name it so you can repeat it on purpose, not by luck.

```json
{
  "notes": [
    {
      "note": "Before playing a scripted beat — reveal OR elicitation — check whether the learner has already articulated its content in a prior turn. If they have, play the beat as confirmation ('yes — that's exactly what the mortar shows'), not as discovery or a restatement-ask. Same file order, same withheld cards, different illocutionary act.",
      "evidence_quote": "Take only the green mortar line now: what fact does it settle, and what does it leave completely unnamed?",
      "check": "Scan for any tutor turn whose propositional content the learner already stated in an earlier turn (e.g. learner T11: 'That's the cause settled. What's still blank is the hand.'); confirm the tutor marked it as confirmation rather than restaging it as fresh discovery or asking the learner to re-state it."
    },
    {
      "note": "When your question reproduces the structural shape of the immediately preceding one (same two-part ask, same 'keep X out of it' framing) after a clean answer, treat it as a signal you are executing a pattern rather than reading the room, and stop to ask what this beat is for right now.",
      "evidence_quote": "the span failed because its centering was struck before the lime had cured… That's the cause settled. What's still blank is the hand.",
      "check": "Flag consecutive tutor turns with isomorphic question structure; confirm the second was warranted by something missing from the first answer, not a re-run of an already-complete split."
    },
    {
      "note": "When the learner has earned the close, release the final word to them — hand off on the last syllable rather than delivering the conclusion yourself.",
      "evidence_quote": "So the finding starts: the span was brought down by…",
      "check": "Locate the dialogue's culminating conclusion; confirm the learner, not the tutor, speaks the operative final term when they have already assembled the pieces to do so."
    }
  ],
  "memory_patch": {
    "section": "Recurring patterns",
    "op": "add",
    "text": "Track what my lines DO, not just that they're next. A scheduled beat (reveal or elicitation) has two functions that can silently swap: revelation vs. confirmation. Once the learner has spoken the thing themselves, the beat converts to confirmation — play it that way ('yes, exactly'), don't restage it as discovery or ask them to re-state it. This is separable from pacing the file: I can hold back cards (crowsfoot, toll book) in their scripted order while still marking, turn by turn, which of them the learner has already pre-empted. Fast tripwire for one subclass: when my question repeats its own shape after a clean answer, I'm running the instrument I trust rather than reading the room. Counter-example to keep: give away the final word when the learner has earned it (the 'span was brought down by… / …Oswin' handoff) — that's withholding paying a dividend, not deferring one."
  },
  "confidence": 0.8
}
```
